    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the instance metrics and cpu/memory usage look pretty stable, so maybe it isnt a bottleneck on the instance itself. could it be something in the VPC or the NAT gateway? or maybe some weird timeout setting in the security group or NACLs that triggers when the connection volume spikes? i'm trying to rule out anything that would cause a sudden drop in the connection.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If CPU and memory are stable, the next likely culprits are the network components themselves, such as the NAT Gateway or the underlying VPC routing/firewalling. Check the NAT Gateway logs or associated metrics, as high traffic volume can sometimes cause connection state table exhaustion on the gateway. Also, thoroughly review your Network ACLs (NACLs); even if security groups allow traffic, NACLs operate at a subnet level and can silently drop packets if return traffic isn't explicitly permitted during a spike.",
      "source": "target",
